      "content": "We can use a single pass through the string and keep track of the longest palindromic substring seen so far. We'll use a helper function to expand around the center of the palindrome. This approach is O(n) and should be fast enough for your use case.\n\n```python\ndef longest_palindrome(s):\n    def expand_around_center(s, left, right):\n        while left >= 0 and right < len(s) and s[left] == s[right]:\n            left -= 1\n            right += 1\n        return s[left + 1:right]\n\n    res = \"\"\n    for i in range(len(s)):\n        # odd length palindrome\n        odd_palindrome = expand_around_center(s, i, i)\n        if len(odd_palindrome) > len(res):\n            res = odd_palindrome\n\n        # even length palindrome\n        even_palindrome = expand_around_center(s, i, i + 1)\n        if len(even_palindrome) > len(res):\n            res = even_palindrome\n\n    return res\n```\n\nThis solution works by maintaining a running maximum length palindrome seen so far. It checks for both odd and even length palindromes by expanding around the center of",
